hms’s “Bitteres zu sagen denkst du,” op. 32, no. 7: A Literary Key to Musical Performance? -- tRomantic Overtones in Contemporary German Literature -- tRobert Schneider’s Schlafes Bruder — A Neo-Romantic Musikernovelle? -- tNotes on the Contributors -- tNotes on the Editors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEssays on the synthesis of the musical and literary arts in German Romanticism.The interrelationship between music and literature reached its zenith during the Romantic era, and nowhere was this relationship more pronounced than in Germany. Many representatives of literary and philosophical German Romanticism held music to be the highest and most expressive, quintessentially Romantic art form, able to convey what cannot be expressed in words: the ineffable and metaphysical. The influence was reciprocal, with literature providing a rich source of inspiration for German composers of both instrumental and vocal music, giving rise to a wealth of new forms and styles. The essays in this volume are selected from papers presented at an international, interdisciplinary conference held at University College Dublin in December 2000, and include contributions from Germanists, musicologists, comparatists, and performance artists. This interdisciplinarity makes for informed and complementary approaches and arguments. The essays cover not only the "Romantic" nineteenth century (commencing with the early Romanticism of the Jena circle), but also look ahead to the legacy, reception, and continuation of German Romanticism in the modern and postmodern ages. Alongside new readings of familiar and established writers and composers such as Goethe, Hoffmann, Wagner, and Schubert, a case is made for other figures such as Wackenroder, Novalis, Schlegel, Schumann, Brahms, Liszt, and Berlioz, as well as less-known figures such as Ritter, Schneider, and Termen, and for a reconsideration of questions of categorization. The essays will appeal to readers with a wide variety of academic, musical, and literary interests.Siobhán Donovan is a Lecturer in the Department of German at University College Dublin. Robin Elliott is Jean A. Chalmers Chair in Canadian Music at the University of Toronto.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGerman literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticismvCongresses. 0aGerman literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticismvCongresses. 0aMusic and literaturevCongresses. 0aRomanticismzGermanyvCongresses. 4aGerman Literature. 4aMusic. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aCategorization.  aGerman Composers.  aGerman Romanticism.  aGoethe.  aHoffmann.  aInterrelationship.  aLiterature Inspiration.  aMusic and Literature.  aRitter.  aSchneider.  aSchubert.  aTermen.  aWagner.1 aBach, Stefanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarkhoff, Juergen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarkhoff, Jürgen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aByrne, Lorraine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonovan, Siobhán, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aElliott, Robin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHill, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHodkinson, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuebener, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHübener, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeil, Werner, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLarkin, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/